{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1835a9c7-85ce-45d4-a00d-917d9cd4ee48","content":"The template has a solid foundation but has a few issues to address before publishing:\n\n**🔴 Functional Bug:**\n- The `Framework` symbol has no `replaces` property, so the chosen framework value won't be substituted into your `.csproj` file. Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` to make it functional.\n\n**🟡 Recommended for NuGet:**\n- **Missing `$schema`** — add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation/editor support.\n- **Missing `description`** — important for discoverability on NuGet.\n- **Missing `groupIdentity`** — needed so multiple versions of the template can coexist (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n\n**🟢 Looks good:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `sourceName`, `author`, `classifications`, `tags` are all correctly defined.\n\nIn short: **not ready yet** — at minimum fix the `Framework` symbol's missing `replaces` and add a `description`. Want me to apply these fixes?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dd575143-eef1-4e8a-ae2f-baaa4e513bd0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nKey issues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but strongly recommended for validation and editor support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet template packs so multiple versions of the same template can coexist.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Related to groupIdentity, helps determine which version wins when multiple are installed.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Minor, but commonly set for project templates.\n\n\n5. **`defaultValue` references `net9.0`** — That's fine, but the real problem is the `Framework` symbol lacks a `replaces` property, so it won't actually substitute the target framework in the .csproj file even though it's defined as a choice parameter.\n\nLooking at what else is missing: there's no `$schema`, no `description` for NuGet discoverability, no `groupIdentity` for template packs, and no `preferNameDirectory` which is recommended for project templates. The `sourceName` handling is solid for namespace replacement, but without the `replaces` on the Framework symbol, the template won't do what it's supposed to do.","outputTokens":732,"requestId":"AC31:D09D:134059:17CB61:69F54B90"},"id":"87c75541-7e84-41b7-a90a-706264951eb7","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:56:00.644Z","parentId":"69fdb34a-49f7-4ba2-94b6-ed6ed7eec4a4"}
